V\u000aIn virtue of the fact that it's a story told via a sequence of recorded images projected in swift succession to give the illusion of movement, Step Up 3D can be classified as a film.
p1
aVBut it's certainly not the type of thing we're normally talking about when we talk about a film.
p2
aVIt's more like a circus, or a West End musical, mixed with the cliches of sports movies and rom-coms into a cheese-infused broth of doubtful artistic value.
p3
aVA decent script, believable characters, acting ability - measured against any of these traditional benchmarks, Step Up 3D is horrendous.
p4
aVBut, as with many classic action movies, these things are simply irrelevant to Step Up 3D.
p5
aVIn place of the one-note characters, ridiculous plotting and spectacular explosions offered by said action movies, Step Up 3D offers one-note characters, ridiculous plotting and spectacular 3D dance sequences.
p6
aVIf the idea of spectacular 3D dance sequences thrills you, this is your movie.
p7
aVIf it does not, you now know all you need to know about Step Up 3D and can leave this page.
p8
aVPerhaps you'd like to read about some world cinema?
p9
aVOther current cinema releases?
p10
aVOr maybe have a look at what's on telly?
p11
aVEnjoy.
p12
aVSo anyway, spectacle fans, now the player haters have left, let's jam.
p13
aVThe first five minutes of Step Up 3D are everything you might fear.
p14
aVInside these first minutes, people talk super earnestly to camera, saying things like "dance has vocabulary", "everybody's a dancer" and "maybe we're all plugged into the same song."
p15
aVYuck.
p16
aVDon't worry, minutes later we're plunged into a New York breakdance sequence that transfers us - via a police chase conducted using the medium of dance-inflected parkour (used for no good reason to jump through a hotdog stand) - to the warehouse/nightclub that our lead hunk o' bland (Rick Malambri) introduces thusly: "Welcome to my house.
p17
aVThe house of pirates."
p18
aVThis is, needless to say, hilarious, and once you realise you're essentially watching a kind of latter day JM Barrie's Lost Boys with a penchant for limited edition gun-metal Nikes and implausible dance routines, the whole thing makes sense and you can sit back, soak up the audacious choreography and wee yourself laughing at the overblown cliches, camp dialogue and utter seriousness with which the actors appear to be taking this arrant nonsense.
p19
aVHow can you not find a space in your heart for a 21st century villain saddled with the name Julien?
p20
aVOr with the guy tasked with hissing "What are you doing here, Julien?"
p21
aVwith a straight face.
p22
aVThis is pure tosh, but in such a goofy, harebrained way that I found it impossible to dislike.
p23
aVIn a nutshell: It's called Step Up 3D, and entirely lives up to what that title  promises.
p24
aVIn the parlance of the dancers, it's totally B.FAB.
p25
aVThat's  'born from a boombox', for those of us not fortunate enough to count the  boombox amongst our progenitors.
