aVGrade: B\u000aFast Facts:\u000aStreet Date: March 10, 2015\u000aFormats: Blu-ray and DVD\u000aRuntime: 98 minutes\u000aRated: \u201cPG\u201d\u000aReleased by Twentieth Century Fox Home Entertainment\u000aThe British Museum comes alive in \u201cNight at the Museum: Secret of the Tomb.\u201d\u000a \u000aShare this:FacebookTwitterLinkedInGoogleEmailPrint\u000a
p271
aV\u000aThere are moments, early on, when you worry if it is going to turn out alright.
p272
aVCan he pull it off?
p273
aVIs there really a happy ending to this epic, the adventures of one director and his collaborators to craft a trilogy that will not only dominate the box office of the early 21st century, not only raise the bar for blockbuster films, but in the end - for all its battles, creatures and plucky little hobbits - actually mean something?
p274
aVThis quest is imperiled early on in The Lord Of The Rings: The Return Of The King; you doubt if there are any surprises left in the bag.
p275
aVAfter the two astonishing innovations of The Lord Of The Rings: The Two Towers - Gollum and the stomping legions at the battle of Helm's Deep - the first few bars of Return Of The King still carry the echoes of the previous film.
p276
aVAragorn (Viggo Mortensen), Gandalf (Ian McKellen), Legolas (Orlando Bloom) and Gimli (John Rhys-Davies) are celebrating the victory at Helm's Deep in the halls of Rohan, while Frodo (Elijah Wood), Sam (Sean Astin) and Gollum (Andy Serkis) are still on their trek into Mordor.
p277
aVThere is a striking prologue that takes us back to the crucial moment in Gollum's life, when he was still a simple Riverfolk called Smeagol, but as we riffle through the various sub-plots and characters of the trilogy, reviving them with a scene here, a speech there, the apprehension arises that Return Of The King will disappoint.
p278
aVThere are too many slo-mos set to pan pipes, there is exposition cut against a derisory battle in the ruins of Osgilith.
p279
aVWe have been here before and the return will lack the startling novelty of our first trip.
p280
aVBut put these doubts out of your mind.
p281
aVDo not think for one minute that Return Of The King fails to meet the considerable expectations that have grown up on the back of previous instalments.
p282
aVYou could open an entire can of hyperbole over this film, and still run short of adjectives to praise its majesty.
p283
aVStill, let's try.
p284
aVNo doubt there will be a few minor spoilers along the way.
p285
aVAfter mopping up the carnage at the close of the Two Towers, the various pieces of the chess game are moved into place for the mother-of-all-battles at the Gondorian stronghold of Minas Tirith.
p286
aVPippin (Billy Boyd) is taken to the city by Gandalf after a ferocious encounter with a Palantir (a black crystal ball).
p287
aVThis shocking, searing experience of sorcery heaves us on our way; the adventure resumes.
p288
aVAs the armies of Mordor approach, the palette darkens.
p289
aVSam and Frodo exist under perpetual gloom, their pallors graying with hunger and exhaustion.
p290
aVFatalism is in the air.
p291
aVAs the fellowship embark upon their various missions, Merry admits "I just don't know what is going to happen".
p292
aVLegolas speaks of a "sleepless malice" rising against them.
p293
aVEven Gandalf admits that the odds are hopeless, death certain; "There was never much of a hope.
p294
aVJust a fool's hope."
p295
aVOverwhelmingly, this is a film about death.
p296
aVNot just in its bodycount (although the colossal battle scenes probably do set a new record for on-screen deaths, even if they are the killing of computer-generated hordes).
p297
aVThe battles - whether it is the Nazgûls swooping over the carved citadel plucking soldiers from the battlements, or horses disappearing beneath the feet of charging oliphants - turn death into spectacle.
p298
aVBut the speeches of Gandalf, and the friendship between Sam and Frodo turn that spectacle into something more telling.
p299
aVIt is there in the reaction of the steward of Gondor, Denethor (John Noble), to the killing of his beloved son Boromir (Sean Bean, way back in the first film); the only character who loses control in the face of death.
p300
aVIf these films have an overarching theme it is courage in the face of the insurmountable odds of your own mortality.
p301
aVOr as Aragorn puts it, as he leaps into an unknown, "I do not fear death".
p302
aVOr Gimli the dwarf, when regarding another suicidal mission; "Certainty of death?
p303
aVSmall chance of success?
p304
aVWhat are we waiting for?"
p305
aVThe film is at its most moving when we are watching the fear play across the faces of our heroes, and the nameless ranks of men who stand against Sauron's horrors.
p306
aVAlong with the high bodycount, there is a very high weepie count too, the sobs inspired as much by this bravery as by grief.
p307
aVOn a lighter note, the fans who have squirreled out sexual subtexts in the relationships between the hobbits as well as, say, Aragorn and Legolas, will find plenty of boxes to tick here.
p308
aVThe Fellowship look longingly at one another.
p309
aVAlso Aragorn, as he ascends to his birthright as King Of Gondor, single-handedly drags the patriarchal beard back into fashion.
p310
aVAlthough it is customary to praise the achievements of the special effects department, this trilogy's most startling achievement is its storytelling; every time the longeurs of exposition or the details of various races and myths threaten your suspension of disbelief, the three-handed scenes between Sam, Frodo and Gollum bring back intimacy and acuity of character.
p311
aVThis focus tightens around the ring itself; the very small thing at the heart of this epic that stands for a very large theme.
p312
aVA small round band of gold that magnifies the evil in every heart and represents man's inexhaustible appetite for power.
p313
aVAgainst this ubiquitous evil stands man's improbable will to persist despite the monstrous nature of his condition; born to die, yet able to face this tragedy with courage and equanimity.
p314
aVAs Gandalf puts it, "Death is just another path which we all must take."
p315
aVThe greatest cinematic event of a generation is over, leaving behind it a thoughtful silence.\u000a
p316
aV\u000aHayao Miyazaki, the master of refined and (mostly) traditional animation, probably couldn't make a bad film.
p317
aVBut with Howl's Moving Castle he fails to top his previous films, Princess Mononoke (1997) and the Oscar-winning Spirited Away (2001).
p318
aVAs with his 1986 film Castle In The Sky, Howl's Moving Castle is adapted from the work of Diana Wynne Jones, the British fantasy writer and onetime student of both JRR Tolkien and CS Lewis.
p319
aVCastle In The Sky is actually her sequel to Howl's Moving Castle, and both films are set in the same world: a land that resembles Europe around the turn of the 19th century.
p320
aVHere, industrialisation and technology are still picturesque.
p321
aVSide by side with this ordinary human society is a world of magic, which is more tangibly threatening than the new belching steam trains and cars.
p322
aVIn a city of Germanic, candy-coloured buildings lives Sophie (voiced by Emily Mortimer in the American dub), a shy, hardworking hat-maker.
p323
aVShe's flung into an adventure - as Miyazaki's young heroines generally are - when she has a back alley encounter with Howl (Christian Bale), a notorious wizard who is reputed to eat the hearts of beautiful young women.
p324
aVHe doesn't eat Sophie's heart; instead he sweeps her off as he's being pursued by mysterious shadowy creatures.
p325
aVThese are the minions of the Witch of the Waste (Lauren Bacall), a sometime employee of the royal court and former lover of Howl, who now has it in for him.
p326
aVUnluckily for Sophie, she's caught up in their battle and the Witch transforms her into an old woman (who is then voiced by Jean Simmons).
p327
aVWith consummate pragmatism, Sophie says to herself, "This isn't so bad.
p328
aVYou're still in pretty good shape and your clothes finally suit you," then heads off alone into the Wastes.
p329
aVHere, she encounters another seemingly cursed entity, a mute scarecrow she dubs Turniphead.
p330
aVHe leads her through the cold until she reaches the "moving castle" - a remarkable clanking construction that lumbers across the landscape thanks to the power of resident fire demon Calcifer (Billy Crystal).
p331
aVSophie, with nowhere else to go, sets herself up as cleaner for Howl's household, which also includes a young apprentice (Josh Hutcherson).
p332
aVBut as she grows used to her new body, and bonds grow between the members of this peculiar "family", a terrible mechanised warfare eats its way across the land and threatens the idyll.
p333
aVIt's a fabulous set-up, but unfortunately it lends itself to narrative convolutions that contrast with the immediacy of Spirited Away or Miyazaki's earlier films.
p334
aVThe royal household, led by Howl's former mentor Suliman (Blythe Danner), is caught up in the war but it's never entirely clear who is fighting whom, or why.
p335
aVPerhaps this ambiguity is intentional, highlighting a sense of the futility of conflict.
p336
aVBut as we see Howl, in the form of a giant flying bird, sweeping through fire-fights and battling other magical creatures, it's hard to fathom the implications.
p337
aVIn one battle scene, the question arises: "Is it the enemy's or one of ours".
p338
aVThe answer is, "What difference does it make?"
p339
aVAt its heart, the film is about Sophie discovering her true self, Howl discovering his, the Witch hers, and even Calcifer his.
p340
aVThe whole thing is a jumble of journeys of self discovery set against Miyazaki's beautiful, evocative worlds.
p341
aVIn one scene the old Sophie, taking a break from her chores in the castle, sits beside a mountain lake, soaking in the scenery.
p342
aVThe majesty of the mountains and the natural world is contrasted with the harshness of the society, where the seemingly benign combination of magic and industrialisation has collapsed into terrible destruction.
p343
aVThere's doubtless a subtext here about the once agrarian Japan developing into the imperial, industrialised nation that felt atomic warfare firsthand.
p344
aVThere are also themes relating to a more general disgust at the wastefulness of warfare, but again, it's not the film's greatest strength.
p345
aVThat lies in the characterisation and, more so, in the characters' relationships with both themselves and each other.
p346
aVIn a nutshell: Another work of great imagination and beauty from Hiyao Miyazaki.
p347
aVMore  muddled than his best films but charming and strangely profound.
