aVFast Facts:\u000aStreet Date: April 23, 2013\u000aFormat: 3D Blu-ray\u000aRuntime: 127 minutes\u000aRated: PG-13\u000aReleased by Universal Studios Home Entertainment\u000a\u000aShare this:FacebookTwitterLinkedInGoogleEmailPrint\u000a
p422
aVThe astounding commercial success of Spielberg's theme-park movie proved once again the power of marketing and awesome special effects to overcome a thin story line and feeble characterisation.
p423
aVAnother surprising aspect of the response was that the film seemed not to depend on a decent-sized cinema screen but proved effective when reduced to little brother telly.
p424
aVA definite tribute to the director's manipulative skill in dotting the overlong proceedings with enough shocks, scary moments and sentimentality to take up the slack.
p425
aVAmid the special effects showcasing and chases, Jurassic Park exhibits the perennial concerns of Michael Crichton - who wrote the source novel.
p426
aVSaid concern is man abusing scientific knowledge and playing God.
p427
aVThe culprit here is Attenborough's John Hammond, an entrepreneur who has used dinosaur DNA taken from blood-sucking mosquitoes that have been preserved in amber to re-create the prehistoric dinosaurs, with the intention of opening the ultimate theme-park cum nature reserve.
p428
aVTo prove that all is well with his proposed park, Hammond is forced to call in three 'experts': paleontologist Dr Alan Grant (Neill), his girlfriend paleo-botanist Dr Ellie Sattler (Dern), and chaos theoretician Dr Ian Malcolm (Goldblum).
p429
aVOh, and sadly some kids are along for the ride too - they are the target audience after all, both for Hammond and for Spielberg.After the initial splendour of viewing a brontosaurus chomping on a tree-top and the thrill of cuddling a sickly tricerotops, things inevitably go sour and the predators make their presence felt.
p430
aVT-Rex reestablishes his reign, this time as king of movie monsters (a kind of bipedal Jaws), while the smaller velociraptors prove their viciousness by hunting and chowing down on various cast members.
p431
aVMuch of the film consists of being chased by dinosaurs and trying to survive.
p432
aVIt's a simple formula, but crudely effective.
p433
aVAttenborough is preposterously bad as Hammond, with an accent as wobbly as his scientific and moral judgement; the performance is only redeemed by his twinkly eyes.
p434
aVThe rest of the cast are adequate, but hobbled by under-developed characters.
p435
aVPossibly the rather characterless leads work to the movie's advantage, since no one going to see a dazzling special effects movie needs distracting by a tame scientist's view of very untamed monsters.
p436
aVNot surprisingly, the sound and the computer-generated visuals received Oscars.
p437
aVDaydreaming farm boy Luke Skywalker (Hamill) longs for a life of adventure and finds it when two droids, one carrying a distress signal from the beautiful Princess Leia, turn up on his farm.
p438
aVSeeking out "crazy old wizard" Ben 'Obi-Wan' Kenobi (Guiness), Luke embarks on his quest to rescue Leia, enlisting the help of cynical Corellian space pirate Han Solo (Ford), his Wookie co-pilot Chewbacca (Mayhew) and the Millennium Falcon ("the ship that made the Kessel run in less than 12 parsecs") along the way.
p439
aVMade on a relatively low budget ($11m), Star Wars (or Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope to give it its full franchise title) is a relentlessly inventive film.
p440
aVThe attention to minute details gives it a rich texture; there are some fantastic set-pieces (Leia's rescue from the Death Star, the X-Wing dogfights), and Lucas binds the whole film together with a hokey religion (The Force) and fatalistic story lifted from Greek mythology.
p441
aVWhile Ford famously dismissed the script (complaining that, "You can type this shit, but you can't say it"), Lucas manages to get away with it by making everyone take it seriously - although Ford can often be seen smirking his way through some of the more clunky lines.
p442
aVThen there's the rousing score by John Williams.\u000a																
