aVIngmar Bergman is famed for his pessimism and a wryly ironic attitude, which frequently dissolves into anguish and despair.
p1086
aVBergman films are hardly universal fare and they're ludicrously at odds with multiplex values.
p1087
aVIt's doubly ironic, then, that Wild Strawberries, if it were to suffer the indignities of a remake, could easily be turned into superior Hollywood feelgood material.
p1088
aVWoody Allen paid extensive homage to it in Deconstructing Harry, another story of a world weary highbrow returning to his alma mater.
p1089
aVWild Strawberries is the story of an ageing doctor, Professor Isak Borg (a wonderful performance from Victor Sjöström), who describes himself, frankly, as an old pedant with no need or time for other people.
p1090
aVOff the cuff, he decides to drive nine hours to a ceremony where he will be honoured for his lifelong devotion to medicine.
p1091
aVHe's accompanied on the journey by his daughter-in-law, Marianne (Thulin), who makes no secret of her dislike for the icy, empty and self-satisfied Isak.
p1092
aVThe story, always laden with symbolism, flashes back from Isak's  troubled present to his youth, and shifts between dreams and reality.
p1093
aVAt  Marianne's prompting, and with the help of a trio of young people he  picks up en route, Isak considers his life choices, revisiting the early  disappointments and betrayals that conspired to make him who he is.
p1094
aVDelightfully, Isak acts on this new self-knowledge, opening himself up  to the world after so many years of icy disengagement.
p1095
aVThis is hardly  the stock Bergman unhappy ending, although it's worth remembering he was  adept at comedy, as shown in Smiles Of A Summer Night, among  others.
p1096
aVBut the warm-heartedness of the story makes it tremendously  accessible, and the story never spills over into sentimentality.
p1097
