aV\u000aPixar continue the trend of producing American cinema's finest family entertainment with Finding Nemo, which consists of two stories in parallel: one a quest, the other an escape story (which has passing similarities with Chicken Run).
p1164
aVBoth begin at home on the reef, where Marlin (voiced by Brooks) obsesses over his Nemo (Gould), his only remaining family as a result of a predator snaffling his wife and all but one of their "over 400 eggs".
p1165
aVSick of his father's over-protectiveness ("I promise I will never let anything happen to you," Marlin declared to his last egg), Nemo ventures beyond the reef's "drop-off" into open water.
p1166
aVBad timing - he's taken by divers and finds himself in a tank in a dentist's surgery in Sydney.
p1167
aVThere, he's befriended by the other residents, including starfish Peach (Janney) and Moorish Idol fish Gill (Dafoe), the leader of the tank community who's constantly planning escape attempts (mainly fixated with the toilet - "All drains lead to the ocean!").
p1168
aVThey're a good bunch, but Nemo is depressed.
p1169
aVWorst still, he's due to become a pet to the dentist's sadistic "fish-killer" niece.
p1170
aVSo the escape plans become more desperate.
p1171
aVMarlin, though he doesn't know it, has a race against time.
p1172
aVAs his quest starts, Marlin meets Dory (DeGeneres), a thoroughly forgetful blue tang fish.
p1173
aV"Is this some kind of practical joke?"
p1174
aVMarlin asks of her supposed idiocy.
p1175
aV"I suffer from short-term memory.
p1176
aVIt runs in my family.
p1177
aVAt least I think it does," she replies.
p1178
aVFinding a mask dropped by one of the divers who took Nemo, the pair head for an address in Sydney.
p1179
aVA plot based on travelling the ocean allows Pixar to indulge in a wonderful array of scenarios and characterisation.
p1180
aVSo, the pair meet three Aussie sharks (Humphries, Bana, Spence), who have a self-help collective where they get together to renew their vows - as Humphries' Great White Bruce puts it: "I am a nice shark, not a mindless eating machine.
p1181
aVFish are friends not food."
p1182
aVThen they encounter a shoal that does impressions by forming the shapes of things - including poor, miserable Marlin himself - becoming an arrow to point them to the East Australian Current.
p1183
aVA more dangerous situation arises when the pair find themselves in the thick of a mass of jellyfish.
p1184
aVRelief is then provided by a group of turtles riding the current, like surfers.
p1185
aVIndeed, Crush the turtle is voiced by writer-director Andrew Stanton in true surfer-stoner style ("Taking on the jellies - you've got serious thrill issues, dude.
p1186
aVAwesome.").
p1187
aVThere's also a pelican, Nigel, voiced by Rush, who helps out Marlin and Dory because he's enjoying their saga and wants to spite the greedy seagulls.
p1188
aVIt's great stuff - vivid, imaginative, wonderfully voiced by all involved and, this being Pixar, it's also cheeky.
p1189
aVThere's a sly dig at the habit in Disney films for characters to burst into song: when Dory tries to comfort Marlin with a tune, he says "Dory - no singing!"
p1190
aVThere are few fart and wee gags ("Don't you people realise we are swimming in our own sh..." says one of the tank fish during an escape plan that involves breaking the filter.
p1191
aV"Shhhhh, here we go!").
p1192
aVThere's even a very gentle knocking of the US ("Humans, they think they own everything."
p1193
aV"Probably American.").
p1194
aVThe biggest laugh comes with Dory speaking whale language (several dialects of it, in fact).
p1195
aVExasperated by her awful noises, Marlin says: "Dory - this is not 'whale'.
p1196
aVYou're speaking like an upset stomach."
p1197
aVThe filmmakers - headed up by Stanton, who also co-wrote and co-directed 1998's A Bug's Life - even manage to squeeze in some neat film references: among them The Shining (Bruce bursting through a door in a sub wreck - "Heeeeere's Brucie!
p1198
aV"), The Birds (a high angle view of gulls crowding), and The Perfect Storm (a fishing boat during the denouement).\u000a
p1199
aVSince 'misery memoirs' are now as grimly familiar as the daytime TV shows that have popularized them in recent years, it's little wonder the phrase has become banal almost to the point of meaninglessness.
p1200
aVFeaturing some of the most relentlessly grim production design in recent British cinema and a protagonist who suffers cruel violence from most people he encounters in the film, Nic Moran's adaptation of Kevin Lewis' best-selling autobiographical novels is a stark reminder of its true sense.
p1201
aVFrom the moment we meet Kevin, dumped on a roadside following a savage beating, he's bruised and battered, and - whether through extended flashbacks to his brutally abusive childhood, or in his adult life as a bare-knuckle boxer forced to inhabit London's criminal underworld - rarely a scene goes by where he's not used as a punchbag.
p1202
aVThe effect of portraying such extreme, sustained violence inevitably verges - at best - on the numbing, but here it's the air of parody that's most problematic.
p1203
aVIf you sat down to watch The Kid, blissfully unaware it was modeled on fact rather than fiction, the queasily familiar story arc (mistreated, deprived but bright boy finds love and comes good), characters (inspiring young English teacher makes Shakespeare cool) and motifs (Kevin's only solace is classical music, listened to on Walkman given to him by inspiring young English teacher) would probably make you scoff.
p1204
aVNor does it help that the abominably miscast Natascha McElhone, as Kevin's unhinged mother and chief abuser - fully 'uglied' up, in false teeth, NHS glasses, housecoat, with fag drooping from perma-snarl and a bawling baby surgically attached to her person - is played as a one-dimensional pantomime villain with shades of Janet Street Porter.
p1205
aVRupert Friend's own performance as the fey, softly spoken Kevin is also slightly baffling.
p1206
aVThough final reel footage, of a TV piece featuring Lewis on the sofa with - you've guessed it - Fern Britton, reveals his impersonation to be spot-on.
p1207
aVStill, as with his mother's characterization, though we're supposedly being told Kevin's story through his own eyes, we're in fact only ever shown it - and very opaquely at that.
p1208
aVHis motivations and the source of the evidently remarkable inner strength required for him to transcend his tragic upbringing, even after spending nearly two hours in his company, remain a mystery.\u000a																
p1209
aVThe first of four collaborations between Alfred Hitchcock and David O. Selznick, the legendary producer of Gone With The Wind, was the setting for a clash of two titanic egos.
p1210
aVThey slugged it out for overall creative control of the film, each complaining of interference from the other and both men stated that they had misgivings about the final results.
p1211
aVThey were just about the only doubters, however, as the film proved to be a box office smash as well as garnering no fewer than 11 Oscar nominations (winning two).
p1212
aVIf anything, it's even more appealing today, with the beautifully photographed cars, clothing and scenery providing a handsome evocation of a lost era, in addition to the timeless quality of the excellent storytelling.
p1213
aVUnusually for a Hitchcock film, the screenplay sticks closely to the source novel.
p1214
aVThis is no bad thing as the story is so good and already provides Hitch plenty of opportunity for his particular brand of dark psychological exploration and steadily cranked tension.
p1215
aVThe young wife (Fontaine) of Maxim De Winter (Olivier), the handsome, rich and temperamental owner of the huge stately home Manderley, is struggling to come to terms with her new life.
p1216
aVShe's haunted by the legacy of Maxim's deceased first wife Rebecca and overawed by her housekeeper, the icy and terrifying Mrs Danvers (Anderson).
p1217
aVShe's totally unaware of Rebecca's true nature, however, and that Maxim is concealing a secret that has the potential to destroy him.
p1218
aVFor once Laurence Olivier doesn't ham it up, delivering a clipped, splendidly moody and even subtle performance.
p1219
aVWhat's more, and equally rare for the great thesp, he imbues his character with great natural warmth, ensuring our sympathy stays with him, no matter how great his crimes seem to be.
p1220
aVOlivier's chemistry with Joan Fontaine sets the screen alight - an impressive achievement if credence is given to the stories that he barely had the time of day for the actress, furious that Vivien Leigh (his first choice for the role and girlfriend at the time) didn't get the part.Naturally, Hitchcock is said to have used this situation to his advantage, teasing the young ingénue Fontaine (she was just 21) mercilessly, while encouraging the rest of the cast to treat her coldly.
p1221
aVThe tactic led to a performance that strikes just the right tone of diffidence, nerviness and downright terror and goes a long way to proving that the young star was far more than just a pretty face.
p1222
aVThe biggest acting credit has to go to Judith Anderson, however, whose steel-faced spectral Mrs Danvers casts a dark shadow in every scene she appears in and has quite rightly become a cinema icon.
p1223
aVEverything else works too.
p1224
aVThere's crisp black-and-white cinematography, a script loaded with morbid humour and sharp dialogue as well and a terrific score used with Hitchcock's usual precision to create a delicious sense of suspense and unease.
p1225
aVIt all combines to create an atmospheric gem, that's as enjoyable as it is impressive.\u000a																
p1226
aVRent this film now on Film4oD\u000a \u000aJust when the ultra-ironic, ultra-violent thriller seemed to have been done to death by Tarantino and his acolytes, along came the Coen brothers to breathe fresh life into the genre.
