aVA few brief observations culled from my recent article on sequels and remakes in the magazine:\u000aEach movie in Disney-Pixar\u2019s Toy Story franchise conforms to a strict narrative template: led by Woody (Tom Hanks), the vintage cowboy doll, a clan of animated toys get separated from their beloved master, Andy, and have to fight their way home.
p1496
aVIn Toy Story 2, the enemy was a venal collector.
p1497
aVIn Toy Story 3, Andy is off to college and his toys are once again playing dodgeball with oblivion.
p1498
aVWill it be the attic?
p1499
aVA yard sale?
p1500
aVNo, they\u2019re donated to a daycare centre\u2014a prison camp ruled with an iron paw by a strawberry-scented stuffed bear.
p1501
aVWhile the franchise\u2019s sentimental mould is inviolable, this sequel has a darker, more satirical edge.
p1502
aVSome of the Orwellian daycare toys are quite scary, like the mad-eyed, cymbal-crashing monkey on surveillance duty, or the big, blank-eyed baby doll.
p1503
aVAnd in an apocalyptic set piece, the toys are sent on a harrowing flume ride through trash shredders to landfill hell.
p1504
