aVGrade: D\u000aFast Facts:\u000aStreet Date: March 6, 2015\u000aFormats: Blu-ray and DVD\u000aRuntime: 123 minutes\u000aReleased by Lionsgate Home Entertainment\u000aHello from the Capital City, my friends.
p2177
aVI am Peeta.
p2178
aVShare this:FacebookTwitterLinkedInGoogleEmailPrint\u000a
p2179
aV\u000a\u000a\u000aDeparting from the battle royale format of the two previous Hunger Games instalments, Mockingjay \u2013 Part 1 plunges the franchise into deeper terrain.
p2180
aVFiguratively, with the pic continuing Katniss Everdeen\u2019s trauma-fuelled mental disintegration and its subject matter becoming bleaker and more violent, as well as the literally underground setting in which much of Mockingjay\u2019s talk of revolution plays out.
p2181
aVAgainst this deep bunker backdrop the cast spend a lot of time sporting unflattering jumpsuits and talking about what is to come in the next chapter, truncated storytelling that hampers this working as a standalone pic.
p2182
aVYes, there is plenty of narrative to work through, and the performances and events that unfold deserve the breathing space that splitting Mockingjay into two films allows.
p2183
aVBut that makes for all build-up and little payoff, lacking a blockbuster set piece finale (even as it tries to make the most of a rebellion skirmish and an aerial commando raid).
p2184
aVThankfully there\u2019s an emotional climax, a cliffhanger that\u2019s less deflating than that of Catching Fire and will further enthuse the audience to see Part 2 - not that they really need any assistance at this point.
p2185
aVDirector Francis Lawrence continues his knack for avoiding obvious, emotionally overwrought moments, something he\u2019s aided considerably in by Lawrence\u2019s expectedly excellent performance.
p2186
aVThe whole franchise has benefited immensely from the inner turmoil she brings to life, and no more so than here.
p2187
aVFor swathes of the film, Katniss has little to do but react to the actions of others, though she does get to blow stuff up with her bow and enjoy a literal save the cat moment.
p2188
aVAnd until Part 2, that\u2019s the most you\u2019re gonna get.
p2189
aV\u2018The Hunger Games: Mockingjay \u2013 Part 1\u2032 Movie Times\u000a\u000a
p2190
aV\u000aThe most enduring image The Hunger Games: Mockingjay - Part 1 offers is an eyeball-searing hell-scape of incinerated corpses, their ribs poking through blackened, immolated flesh.
p2191
aVThis is not Harry Potter, this is not the Twilight saga - The Hunger Games is here to offer an in-your-face critique of the abuse of power and neither the characters nor the material is about to shy away from the issues.
p2192
aVBoth book and film understand and want show their audience that contemporary wars are fought as much through media as they are on the battlefield.
p2193
aVOr rather, while wars have always been fought through the media, these days the media is also in the thick of the actual fight: cameras can be sent out unobtrusively into the field to capture "the truth," though it is of course still in the interpretation of these truths that hearts and minds are won and lost.
p2194
aVAs the film opens, we pick up with Katniss (Jennifer Lawrence), furious that the rebel alliance led by President Coin (a frosty Julianne Moore) plotted to save her from the Hunger Games at the expense of her more expendable companions.
p2195
aVThey counter that she is their mascot - the emblem of the revolution; they needed her to survive.
p2196
aVAs she refuses to co-operate, they realize they also need her good will.
p2197
aVThe majority of the film is about negotiating that co-operation and how to play it on camera once they finally have her onside.
p2198
aVThe script, by Peter Craig and Danny Strong (Buffy fans may recognise Strong for his onscreen work as nerdy Jonathan Levinson), has a lot of fun with Katniss Everdeen's legendary awkwardness.
p2199
aVPlutarch Heavensbee (Philip Seymour Hoffman in his last role) attempts to media train Katniss into a serviceable mouth-piece for their cause, leading to comic scenes of desperation as he and his team realise quite what a dud screen presence she is when asked to play-act the revolution.
p2200
aVIt's a smart excuse for the narrative to take Katniss out to where the action is, which is also what we want as an audience: we need action, even if it is all being staged for our benefit.
p2201
aVIt's hard to shake the feeling that this film doesn't have a particularly cinematic arc, and that this is partly a consequence of carving two films out of one book.
p2202
aVThere is a lot to get through in that third book, but much of it is internal and emotional, to do with how Katniss wrestles with everything that is demanded of her and with her feelings for Peeta, who is mostly restricted to brief onscreen glimpses as the Capitol cranks out its own propaganda making use of their most influential hostage.
p2203
aVThese brief glimpses of Peeta, Caesar Flickerman (Stanley Tucci) and President Snow (Donald Sutherland having more fun than anyone else in the film) really do pop - if only there were more of them.
p2204
aVPerhaps it proves Suzanne Collins' satirical point that the absence of the Capitol in this instalment is so keenly felt.
p2205
aVThe world of Panem is named for the Latin tag "panem et circenses": the idea of using "bread and circuses" to distract a population from their lack of real freedom by giving them a glittering show.
p2206
aVWe're so used to blockbusters on this scale delivering precisely that show, it's a little disconcerting to realise that you have indeed been conditioned to miss it when it's left out in favour of something more ideologically sound.
p2207
aVWe want more of the decadent Capitol and their razzle dazzle; the revolution is a little sombre.
p2208
aVAnd that's exactly how the Capitol's real life equivalents maintain their power, by making radical change seem so crashingly colourless.\u000a
p2209
aVThe road to Hollywood is littered with the corpses of pop stars who've tried their hand at acting and found the world wasn't ready for their close-ups (stand up Michael Jackson, Maria Carey, Madonna).
p2210
aVWhich is probably why 8 Mile has the oddball pairing of Eminem and Curtis Hanson.
p2211
aVJust as Dr Dre lent Marshall Mathers III credibility when he emerged onto the hip hop scene a few years ago, Wonder Boys director Hanson gives the rapper cinematic legitimacy for his big screen debut - and, man, does he come off well.
p2212
aVAs Rabbit, an aspiring MC from a broken home who's trying to work his way up through Detroit's black hip-hop clubs, he's essentially playing a fictionalised version of himself.
p2213
aVHowever, rather than turn 8 Mile into an Eminem vanity project, Hanson and writer Scott Silver (Johns) hone the star's personality traits to create a strong, socially-aware character-driven drama.
p2214
aVLike Hanson's L.A.
p2215
aVConfidential, 8 Mile has a strong sense of place.
p2216
aVThe title refers to the street that separates Detroit's affluent white neighbourhoods from its poor black ones and Hanson - by way of Amores Perros cinematographer Rodrigo Prieto's fluid-but-raw hand-held work - brilliantly captures the chaos of a once great industrial city gone to ruin.
p2217
aVRabbit, or Jimmy Smith Jr (Eminem), is the nominal white kid from the wrong side of the tracks who dreams of using his MC skills to get out of Detroit's run-down 313 area.
p2218
aVBy day he works in a steel plant, at night he works on his lyrics in the trailer he shares with his boozy, bingo-addicted white-trash mother Stephanie (Basinger) and adoring six-year-old sister Lily (Greenfield).
p2219
aVIn the opening scenes we see Rabbit choke in front of a sea of black faces at a free-style battle hosted by his friend Future (Phifer).
p2220
aVHe scuttles off stage to catcalls of "Vanilla Ice" - something the real Slim Shady endured on his way up.
p2221
aVThe rest of the film is built around Rabbit finding his voice.
p2222
aVOn the surface it's a hip-hop Rocky, but while the subtext of Stallone's film was about putting a smart-talking black man - namely Muhammad Ali - in his place, 8 Mile is about defusing racial tension and focussing attention on the economic deprivation that intensifies division.
p2223
aVAs Future tells Rabbit: "When they hear you, it's not gonna matter what colour you are."
p2224
aVIf there's a fault with this set-up it's that the women are under-served.
p2225
aVRabbit's love interest Alex (Brittany Murphy - looking like Courtney Love circa 1991), is a wannabe model who is trying to make it by screwing someone to help her get a portfolio together.
p2226
aVAs for Basinger, her moment of redemption comes when she wins the bingo.
p2227
aVFor a film that skilfully negotiates racial and class-issues with a minimum of clichés, it's a little depressing that it is so reductive with its female characters.\u000a																
p2228
aVOkay then, so you haven't seen the original Inglorious Bastards.
p2229
aVWorry no longer - Quentin Tarantino's latest has as much to do with Enzo G Castellari's exploitation movie as Ice-T has to do with the history of the East India Company.
p2230
aVAnd those fretting that QT might still be on a Grind House kick can also calm themselves.
p2231
aVDeath Proof this ain't.
p2232
aVHis best film since Pulp Fiction it most certainly is.
p2233
aVNot that everyone will see it as such.
p2234
aVIndeed, you wouldn't have to try too hard to find Inglourious Basterds a trying exercise in excess and homage.
p2235
aVToo in thrall to other movies and gratuitous violence the cynic might say.
p2236
aVThe trouble is, adopting this sort of position is to deny yourself a lot of entertainment.
p2237
aVBecause Inglourious Basterds is as much fun as you can have in a cinema without embarrassing an usher.
p2238
aVIt's 1943, and the war is in the balance.
p2239
aVJewish avengers, comedy Nazis (both Hitler and Goebbels are played for laughs), a veiled celebration of the cinema of Leni Riefenstahl - you'll find all human life in the Inglourious Basterds.
p2240
aVIncluding a sadistic Standartenfuhrer known as "The Jew Hunter", played by the awesome Christoph Waltz .
p2241
aVAn Austrian actor resident in London, Tarantino has said he wouldn't have made Inglourious Basterds had he not discovered Waltz.
p2242
aVWitty, slimy, vile, winning, subtle, overstated - his is the sort of complete performance upon which careers are founded.
p2243
aVPut bluntly, he's the best thing about Inglourious Basterds, and the film is weaker every moment he's not on screen.
p2244
aVYou could say similar thing about Brad Pitt.
p2245
aVNot that there's anything understated about his 'Aldo The Apache', leader of a Jewish-American platoon operating behind enemy lines.
p2246
aVNo, this is what you'd get if you brought together Clark Gable, Errol Flynn and John Wayne, and then stuck 'em in a blender.
p2247
aVHammy camera-hogging some might cry, but since that's the order of the day here, Pitt's efforts blend seamlessly with Mike Myers' seedy British General Ed Fenech, Diane Kruger's Dietrich-esque Bridget Von Hammersmark, and Eli Roth's muscle-bound, baseball bat-wielding Donny Donowitz.
p2248
aVThere are almost too many highspots to point up.
p2249
aVTake the opening sequence in which Waltz's Hans Lander interrogates a dairy farmer he believes guilty of harbouring Jews.
p2250
aVSure, the whole thing's a steal from The Good, The Bad And The Ugly, but the pacing, tension and dialogue are of a standard previously unseen in Tarantino's cinema.
p2251
aVThe ageing enfant terrible might not have grown up but he's certainly grown. 
p2252
aVIs everything falling apart or is it just us?
p2253
aVIt's been a traumatic start to the new century and then late in the decade comes a supposed Hollywood comic book blockbuster that asks: do we deserve to be saved from the terrorists?
p2254
aVOr has democracy failed, and would we be safer under a fascist regime led by a man dressed as a bat?
p2255
aVChristopher Nolan's The Dark Knight is an annihilating experience, especially if you watch it in the enormous IMAX theatre, a vertiginous phenomenon at the best of times; when that eight storey screen fills up with the scarred, sweating, greasepaint-smeared face of Heath Ledger's Joker, speaking of chaos and the cannibalism lurking under civilisation, the temptation is to run screaming into the night.
p2256
aVThe action is devastating, high-wire and realistic.
p2257
aVThe ideas are even more destructive, presenting Western civilisation as a precarious condition liable to break down when threatened with an enemy it cannot bargain with or buy off, an enemy who is insane and only wants to see it burn.
p2258
aVThat's hyperbole, sure.
p2259
aVBut hyperbole is the great stage upon which the modern mythology of comic book heroes plays out.
p2260
aVThe screenplay written by Jonathan and Christopher Nolan, with additions to the story from David S Goyer, synthesizes crucial elements from two of the greatest Batman comics, Frank Miller's 'The Dark Knight Returns' and Alan Moore's 'The Killing Joke'.
p2261
aVFrom Miller's groundbreaking portrait of an ageing Batman, the screenplay inherits the malign influence of a masked vigilante upon society, and what demons are unleashed as an unintended consequence of the thrilling psychic and social disorder inspired by a Batman.
p2262
aVFrom 'The Killing Joke' it extracts Moore's Joker, a connoisseur of insanity, visiting the same madness that led to his creation upon our heroes.
p2263
aVThe screenwriters have added a third provocation: when the Roman Empire had the barbarians at the gate, they suspended democracy and handed rule over to one man, Caesar, to protect them.
p2264
aVCould Batman be the new Caesar?
p2265
aVThe Dark Knight puts us through the wringer on this one, toying with fascism as a way out of the endless fear and crime before showing, at its close, that even the best of men would be corrupted by the responsibility of being judge, jury and executioner.
p2266
aVChristopher Nolan's first pass at this material was Batman Begins in 2005, a dark and gloomy movie, no doubt, but it needed a dose of the Scarecrow's psychedelic poison to set the citizens of Gotham at one another's throats.
p2267
aVThis time, Heath Ledger's Joker drips fear and disorder into the body politic and the results are far more disturbing.
p2268
aVLedger tragically died after filming was completed, and the premature death of such a coruscating talent contributes a terrible urgency to his performance, rubbing away at your knowledge that the actor was just messing around.
p2269
aVWith his lank unwashed green hair, hunched shoulders and restless tongue, always drawing back the saliva from the scars at the corner of his smile, this Joker is all our fears of the amoral urban dispossessed (he likes his knife crime) multiplied by our terror of the suicide bomber, the killer who cannot be reasoned with, the murderer who wants nothing but our destruction.
p2270
aVHe is Kurt Cobain's self-hatred directed outwards, a nihilist to make Nietzsche quiver.
p2271
aVAgainst the forces of darkness, we have a white knight.
p2272
aVAaron Eckhart's district attorney Harvey Dent, who wages effective war against the upper echelons of Gotham's criminal classes.
p2273
aVTogether with Gary Oldman's Lieutenant Gordon and Christian Bale's Batman, the forces of law and order gain the upper hand.
p2274
aVRachel Dawes, played by Maggie Gyllenhaal, falls in love with Dent, an unexpected twist in affairs as Batman Begins had Rachel - then played by Katie Holmes - all set up to be the love of Bruce Wayne's life.
p2275
aVHarvey and Batman's campaign is so effective that the criminals are forced to turn to the Joker, and so both men are responsible - if not entirely culpable - for the horrors that are unleashed, on the city and on themselves.
p2276
aVThe Dark Knight succeeds where other comic book movies fail because of its bone-crunching physicality.
p2277
aVOn the IMAX screens, even the establishing shots of swooping city vistas are a white-knuckle ride.
p2278
aVWhen the filmmakers flip a 40-foot tractor trailer in the heart of Chicago, you'll never want to see another computer-generated fight sequence again.
p2279
aVThat physicality also comes from the actors.
p2280
aVChristian Bale thinned himself right down for The Machinist and was a raw-boned prisoner of war in Werner Herzog's Rescue Dawn; his martial arts work as Batman makes the close combat sing.
p2281
aVHeath Ledger's Joker is like the wolf in 'Little Red Riding Hood', a mangy and disguised beast with a sardonic wit.
p2282
aVHe achieves more with one nurse's outfit than Jack Nicholson managed in the entirety of Tim Burton's Batman.
p2283
aVIt's only when the second villain of the piece appears, the horrific Two-Face, that we get a glimmer of computerised special effects - the result, by the way, is so bleak and scary that parents are advised against sneaking their little ones into this movie unless they want them to grow up disturbed.
p2284
aVThe supporting cast add vital colour and context.
p2285
aVMichael Caine's Alfred has the wisdom of a battle veteran, and his anecdotes from his time in Burma situate the comic book battle in the actual history of war.
p2286
aVMorgan Freeman's Lucius Fox once again plays Q to Batman's Bond, and provides an ethical check to the hero's flirtation with Big-Brother-style fascism.
p2287
aVGary Oldman's Lieutenant Gordon is the pragmatic face of the good cop who teeters on the edge when his family is threatened.
p2288
aVThe coup de grace of The Dark Knight is its structure.
p2289
aVAn ending seems to come, and emotionally you are drained but prepared for a third film that will complete the trilogy.
p2290
aVThat third film then unfolds before you.
p2291
aVHere the gates of hell open up with the appearance of Two-Face and the further ramifications of the Joker's plan.
p2292
aVToo often superhero films climax with a dull slugfest between computer-generated heroes and villains: here the ending reminds one of Fight Club's tower block-set face-off with something of Sophie's Choice and Michael Mann's Manhunter ; an emotionally draining encounter that ensures the film does not disappear into a flurry of special effects.\u000a																
p2293
aV\u000aIn Christopher Nolan's 2008 comic-book crime epic The Dark Knight, stalwart police lieutenant James Gordon called Batman, the caped crusader, 'the hero Gotham deserves, but not the one it needs right now.'
p2294
aVWhen it comes to Nolan's brand of super-sized cinema, though, you could say the opposite is true.
p2295
aVNolan's focus on spectacle, celluloid and smart narrative concepts is a very necessary ally in the ongoing battle to keep film relevant as a mass-market entertainment.
p2296
aVThen again, no one deserves to sit through almost three hours of rear-numbing cinema unless there's good reason to.
p2297
aVAt just shy of 170 minutes, Interstellar is Nolan's longest film to date, but it's also by turns his most brazenly ambitious and mind-numbingly ponderous.
p2298
aVMatthew McConaughey caps off his 'McConaissance' arc from smarmy romcom lead to indie darling to Oscar winner by leading this, the most ambitious blockbuster of the year, and lending it some required rootsy charm in the process.
p2299
aVHis southern-fried smoothness is a good fit for Cooper, a once-promising pilot reduced to being a farmer and single dad in Nolan's near-future America, which has turned agrarian after successive Dust Bowl-like catastrophes ravage the world's crops.
p2300
aVIt's a compelling start, and the solution, like in many sci-fi stories before it, lies in the stars.
p2301
aV'Solution' is the key term here, as Interstellar reveals that, while Christopher Nolan may court comparisons to the likes of cosmic auteurs Stanley Kubrick (2001) and Terrence Malick (The Tree Of Life), his big scientific and philosophical questions are rarely left unanswered, even when they touch on themes better left just out of comprehension's reach.
p2302
aVThe effect is not unlike Inception, which resembled a film about dreams made by someone who had never dreamt: this is a sci-fi film that rejects the mysteries of the galaxy for the comfort of resolution.
p2303
aVWhat Interstellar does have is scale in all dimensions, and the worlds envisaged by Nolan, his VFX crew at Double Negative and cinematographer Hoyte Van Hoytema (better known for more intimate fare, such as Her, Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy and Let The Right One In) are as technically accomplished as we've come to expect.
p2304
aVLikewise, Nolan's pulling power with A-grade actors is undiminished, with Michael Caine, Anne Hathaway and a few unbilled surprises willing to strap in for the ride - even if, in Caine and Hathaway's cases, they are primarily engines for elongated scenes of exposition.\u000a
p2305
aV\u000a\u000a\u000aNever has a nearly-three-hour blockbuster enthralled me in the way that Interstellar did.
p2306
aVAfter the grim seriousness and plodding pacing of his Dark Knight films, where Christopher Nolan did his damnedest to provide a real world for an utterly ridiculous character to play in, it\u2019s a relief to see him freed from such constraints.
p2307
aVNot that there isn\u2019t solid science underpinning Interstellar\u2019s world-building (and departing), in fact there\u2019s a ton of it.
p2308
aVThose not interested in cosmological hows and whys may find the necessary infodumps all too frequent, but where Interstellar eclipses Nolan\u2019s creativity as seen onscreen previously is in the sense of awe, wonder and spectacle he\u2019s able to conjure on this trip into the unknown.
p2309
aVThat the film veers all over the place is, to me, one of the things that justifies its length.
p2310
aVGiving himself more of that precious resource, time, to play with (and jettisoning the expected training montage second act), Nolan gets to introduce A-list actors late, indulge in sub-plots that don\u2019t emerge until the final half hour, and take us to some truly spectacular places along the way.
p2311
aVThe cast are good, if not outright great.
p2312
aVAs with other Nolan pics, his ability to construct strong characters powered by real emotion is lacking.
p2313
aVLuckily the likes of McConaughey, Chastain, Caine and even Hathaway (mostly) bring plenty to their performances.
p2314
aVPerhaps this is all sounding ho hum to you.
p2315
aVBut if space travel, sci-fi and visual spectacle appeal, you can\u2019t look past this triumph of the imagination where the wondrous universe is the true star.
p2316
aVInterstellar renders this semi-palatable for mainstream consumption thanks to co-writers Jonathan Nolan and theoretical physicist Kip Thorne.
p2317
aVAdd a director who may not have the singularity of vision possessed by Kubrick (himself flawed), and you\u2019ve still got one of the most watchable self-indulgent projects in ages.
p2318
aV\u2018Interstellar\u2019 movie times\u000a\u000a
p2319
aV\u000aMatthew McConaughey searches for a planet suitable for human life in \u201cInterstellar.\u201d\u000aKudos to Christopher Nolan for trying.
p2320
aV\u201cInterstellar\u201d almost makes it.
p2321
aVBut, the science fiction adventure film has problems after take-off.
p2322
aV\u201cInterstellar\u201d is a flawed but fascinating journey featuring plot elements that seem more Spielbergian than Nolanesque.
p2323
aVAnd, an outrageously unbalanced sound design becomes a major distraction late in the film.
p2324
aVMore on that, later.
p2325
aVA memorable sci-fi has to be more than just special effects.
p2326
aVThe story needs to equal all the razzle-dazzle.
p2327
aV\u201cInterstellar\u201d feels like someone else\u2019s film, a Spielberg retread.
p2328
aVThe story opens with a widower (Matthew McConaughey) trying to keep his family unit functioning while the world literally crumbles into dust clouds.
p2329
aVEarth needs food to feed its seven billion residents.
p2330
aVAnd, that means family farms are of the utmost importance.
p2331
aVFormer engineer/astronaut Cooper (McConaughey) lives in a low-tech world that doesn\u2019t need space travel anymore.
p2332
aVTechnology is on the fritz.
p2333
aVSo, Cooper manages the family farm with his father-in-law (John Lithgow) and his two children, Murph and Tom.
p2334
aVAfter a strange gravitational event in his daughter\u2019s bedroom, Cooper and Murph (Mackenzie Foy) hit the road to find a secret NASA operation planning an intergalactic mission.
p2335
aVIt\u2019s no surprise that Steven Spielberg was interested in this project, since it reportedly was written for him.
p2336
aVAnd, the first 45 minutes is basically \u201cClose Encounters of the Third Kind,\u201d minus the giant mound of mashed potatoes.
p2337
aVCo-screenwriter Jonathan Nolan (Christopher\u2019s brother) likely added the family/unearthly message elements as a way to attract and/or appease Spielberg.
p2338
aVSo, when Christopher Nolan took over as director, the Spielberg elements needed to go.
p2339
aVIt\u2019s not his movie anymore.
p2340
aVNolan would be better served with a complete rewrite.
p2341
aVWhen Cooper agrees to pilot a spaceship through a wormhole in a frantic effort to find a new habitable planet, that\u2019s when the story gets interesting.
p2342
aVAt the secret NASA operation, he meets his old professor (Michael Caine), the man with most of the answers.
p2343
aVThe crew of the Endurance includes the professor\u2019s daughter, Amelia Brand (Anne Hathaway).
p2344
aVRest of the story I will leave to you.
p2345
aVBecause, despite my complaints, I don\u2019t want to keep you from seeing this film or ruin the discovery process.
p2346
aVKeep in mind, Nolan\u2019s worst film is better than most of the crap coming out of Hollywood these days.
p2347
aVNolan used IMAX cameras for much of this production, and it shows.
p2348
aVThe photography is spectacular.
p2349
aVThe special effects are awesome.
p2350
aVSo, what happened with Zimmer\u2019s score?
p2351
aVIt was overpowering in key scenes.
p2352
aVI couldn\u2019t understand the dialogue.
p2353
aVYou could hear the characters speaking, but you could NOT comprehend what they were saying.
p2354
aVNolan says he planned it that way.
p2355
aVHard to believe, unless he\u2019s gone nuts.
p2356
aVThe acting in this space saga is quite excellent.
p2357
aVEspecially, McConaughey.
p2358
aVHe is the perfect everyman to go on this adventure.
p2359
aVAny praise he gets for this film is well-deserved.
p2360
aVFinally, the running time is 169 minutes.
p2361
aVThat\u2019s over three hours, folks.
p2362
aVThe story would have been better served with more specifics on why the earth was becoming uninhabitable.
p2363
aVThe takeaway from \u201cInterstellar\u201d is that Christopher Nolan is human after all.
p2364
aVIt\u2019s a trip marred by sound distortion, but still worthwhile.
