aV"He was some kind of a man... What does it matter what you say about people?"
p2470
aVIt could be Welles' epitaph as much as that of Hank Quinlan, the obese, vile and potentially corrupt US border cop.
p2471
aVIf Welles is to be remembered for something other than Citizen Kane, it would probably be the justly famous opening tracking shot here, the ideal introduction to a perfectly stylized noir.
p2472
aVTouch of Evil had a chequered history.
p2473
aVThe original script by Paul Monash was shelved by B-movie producer Albert Zugsmith.
p2474
aVWelles was employed to act in it, then encouraged to direct too.
p2475
aVHe didn't bother to read the source novel ('Badge Of Evil' by Whit Masterson).
p2476
aVAfter the best part of a decade working in TV or on international features (1955's Mr. Arkadin was a French/Spanish/Swiss production), Welles returned to Hollywood and created another masterpiece.
p2477
aVBut it's amazing the film survived at all - Welles was sacked in post-production and it very nearly never saw the light of day.
p2478
aVInstead, the studio hacked it into a supporting movie, a B-movie.
p2479
aVRestored as per his original notes in the 1990s, Touch Of Evil has emerged near faultless in style and characterisation; a confirmed masterpiece and one of the great American classics.
p2480
aVThe film concerns Mexican narcotics officer Mike Vargas (Heston, in a role that twisted his usual all-American heroic credentials) who is on honeymoon with young American wife Susan (Leigh) in a fictional border town (Los Robles, which was recreated in rundown Venice, California).
p2481
aVVargas gets caught up with political intrigue involving, among others, a sharp-tongued hooker (Dietrich, brilliant) and corrupt local cop Quinlan (Welles, brilliantly vile). 
p2482
aVBased on the 1962 short La Jetée, Terry Gilliam's brilliant dystopian thriller is his finest film yet, with its inevitably stunning visuals, a nail-biting plot, and the casting against type of Bruce Willis and Brad Pitt.
p2483
aVWillis, here remind everybody of his ability to alternate no-brain blocksbusters with smaller, interesting projects, is time-travelling convinct James Cole, who is sent from his futuristic prison back to the 1990s to prevent mankind from being destroyed by a virus which may have something to do with mental patient Jeffrey Goines (Pitt, earning a Golden Globe and an Oscar nomination).
p2484
aVKicking off with a bizarre sci-fi thriller - once sent back, Cole's babblings about the impending human wipeout land him in an institution alongside the clearly barmy Jeffrey - Gilliam goes on to deliver a movie that is not only rich in visual detail but offers an involving, occasionally baffling storyline and builds the tension to positively unbearable levels during the final reel.
p2485
aVWeighing in with a heavyweight work that tops anything he has done since 1992's Unforgiven, Clint Eastwood's boxing saga Million Dollar Baby is a relentlessly unsentimental melodrama that delivers its body-blows when you least expect them.
p2486
aVAfter the somewhat hysterical Mystic River - a flawed work dominated by a powerhouse performance from Sean Penn - this is a far more balanced piece, anchored by three terrific turns and some lean direction from Eastwood.
p2487
aVTo give away the secrets of the plot would be criminal.
p2488
aVSuffice it to say it's a story about redemption that embraces religion, family and social affairs.
p2489
aVEastwood plays grizzled boxing trainer Frankie Dunn, owner of The Hit Pit gym in downtown Los Angeles.
p2490
aVLaced with guilt, when he's not at the gym he's either attending mass (as he has done for 23 years) or writing letters to his estranged daughter, all of which come back marked 'return to sender'.
p2491
aVIf that wasn't enough, he also blames himself for the loss of an eye sustained in the ring by ex-boxer Scrap (Freeman), who Frankie used to train and who now looks after the day-to-day running of the gym.Narrated by Scrap - with Freeman's trademark soothing voice adding resonance to every line - the story sees Frankie reluctant to take his boxers the distance and get them shots at title fights.
p2492
aVWhen his prize asset, Big Willie Little (Colter), dumps him for new management, Frankie is left with little option but to take on a newcomer who has been hanging around the gym.
p2493
aVTrouble is, she's a girl - and he doesn't train girls.
p2494
aVA white trash waitress with a brother in prison, a sister on welfare and a mother who weighs 312lbs, Maggie Fitzgerald (Swank) may have been brought up on the wrong side of the tracks, but slowly she wears Frankie down until he takes her on.
p2495
aVBut, at 32, has she got what it takes to fight professionally?
p2496
aVIf it sounds like a mix of Girlfight and Rocky, nothing could be further from the truth.
p2497
aVEastwood dances around the dreaded clichés of punch-drunk sagas with impressive footwork.
p2498
aVAdapted by Paul Haggis from 'Rope Burns', a collection of short stories by FX Toole, the script has a sardonic wit about it, with Scrap in particular adding some much-needed humour.
p2499
aV"The planet can go back to spinning," he dryly notes, after Frankie, in a rare act of kindness, buys him a cheeseburger.
p2500
aVThere is also a nicely judged sub-plot featuring a weak-kneed wannabe named 'Danger' (Baruchel), desperate to challenge Thomas Hearns for the welterweight title, not knowing he retired years ago.
p2501
aVWith Swank proving that her Oscar for Boys Don't Cry was not a one-off, she is both physically and emotionally credible in her role.
p2502
aVFor once, in the training montage - a boxing movie staple - it actually appears as if her physique is becoming more toned and muscular, proving she really did shed blood, sweat and tears for the part.
p2503
aVAs for Eastwood, here offering his best performance since The Bridges Of Madison County (1995), it's delightful to see that he has once again found it in him to be able to direct himself.
p2504
aVWhile Frankie Dunn is a part less overtly iconic than 'Dirty' Harry Callaghan, Eastwood's turn is finely-judged and completely lacking in vanity - rather like the film itself. 
p2505
aV\u000aTimothy Spall gives an excellent performance as British painter J.M.W.
p2506
aVTurner in Mike Leigh\u2019s \u201cMr.
p2507
aVTurner.\u201d\u000aI\u2019m certainly not an expert on 19th century British painters, but I can imagine that \u201cMr.
p2508
aVTurner\u201d is made with such care that it could be a wonderful introduction to art students studying the life of Joseph Mallord William Turner (1775-1851).
p2509
aVDirector Mike Leigh and actor Timothy Spall have painted their own masterpiece.
p2510
aVTurner\u2019s genius was established early in his career, and Leigh chose to focus on the latter half of the artist\u2019s life when he became even better known and more eccentric.
p2511
aVTurner\u2019s devotion to his ailing father is clear in the film.
p2512
aVAs were the relationships with women that kept him unmarried, by choice, his entire life.
p2513
aVLeigh\u2019s screenplay also captures Turner\u2019s artistic independence, both his stubbornness and epic vision.
p2514
aVGreat accolades can be heaped on Spall\u2019s interpretation of Turner.
p2515
aVDid the artist grunt, groan and speak in spurts?
p2516
aVI don\u2019t know and don\u2019t care.
p2517
aVSpall dives deep and fascinates with his performance.
p2518
aVIt took me several minutes to adjust to his dialect, but I eventually heard every word spoken by this worthy actor.
p2519
aVMost of the ensemble cast checks out as well.
p2520
aVDorothy Atkinson generates sympathy as Hannah Danby, Turner\u2019s devoted housekeeper.
p2521
aVMarion Bailey does an admirable job as Sophia Booth, Turner\u2019s landlady and eventual lover.
p2522
aVShe made Turner\u2019s seaside home a peaceful, desirable retreat.
p2523
aVPaul Jesson excelled as Turner\u2019s father.
p2524
aVHe and Spall played well off each other.
p2525
aVThe mutual love and devotion between these two characters was realized.
p2526
aVThe costumes, the sets, the cinematography transport you magnificently to Turner\u2019s era.
p2527
aVI learned about art history and the human condition.
p2528
aVI\u2019m inspired to know more about the artist and see his works in person, thanks to Mike Leigh, his cast and crew.
p2529
aVThank you.
