p3153
aVThe first five minutes of The Social Network lay the film's cards brilliantly on the table.
p3154
aVAfter a humiliating and totally justified romantic rejection, 19 year old Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg (an utterly on-fire Jesse Eisenberg) returns to his rooms at Harvard, grabs a beer, logs on to his blog and rants bitterly.
p3155
aVIn this he's no different to countless contemporary students.
p3156
aVThe difference emerges as Mark's drunken anger evolves from slagging off the lady in question - "Erica Albright's a bitch.
p3157
aVYou think that's because her family changed their name from Albrecht or because all B.U.
p3158
aVgirls are bitches?"
p3159
aV- to coding a website called Facemash that allows users to compare the hotness of female Harvard undergraduates.
p3160
aVIt's a tiny step down a road that eventually leads to the creation of Facebook.
p3161
aVAs Mark steals women's pictures for Facemash by hacking Harvard's online directories of student photographs college by college, the action cuts between this excluded teen's dorky dorm room and a hedonistic party given by the socially connected elite of Harvard.
p3162
aVScriptwriter Aaron Sorkin (The West Wing) says "We don't know if this party is real or if the party exists in Mark's head as the place where he can't be while he's doing all this, but I think that - like all of us - Mark would like to feel the way other people look."
p3163
aVTrent Reznor (Nine Inch Nails) and Atticus Ross' consistently superb score grinds through this interlocking scene (drink, drugs and truckloads of girls versus coding, computers and pictures of girls), helping bring out all the bitter tensions between Mark's misogynistic fantasy of promiscuous hedonism and the provocative thrill of creating Facemash.
p3164
aVThis, the work of a single, solitary evening - presented as a lonely, intoxicating power trip - sets the stage perfectly for the film to come.The online politics of relationships, the need to not only belong but be at the top, the excitement of rage-fuelled creation and destruction, where exactly inspiration comes from and whether you can own it, the nature of friendship, the nature of competing truths, the impossibility of objectivity - these are huge ideas and The Social Network tackles them head on with a stylish wit.
p3165
aVSorkin tells the story of Facebook, but the film isn't really about Facebook.
p3166
aVIt's about what happens when a timeless antagonist - an intelligent and often very funny but bitter and arrogant post-adolescent male - chances to be born at a time and place when his particular set of abilities and drives are exactly those required to found a new nation state of the online world.
p3167
aVEisenberg wonderfully portrays a character of whom we believe all this without question.
p3168
aVOn the one hand his Mark radiates abundant talent and ambition, on the other he successfully projects the screwed-up bile that stems from his failure to grasp the subtleties of real-world human interaction.
p3169
aVHe understands the rules of the game, but can't or won't play.
p3170
aVEqually, and far more laudably, Mark is also shown throughout to be motivated by a desire to tear down social barriers rooted in tradition and privilege, with Harvard a steaming microcosm of global social hierarchies.
p3171
aVCould there be anything more indicative of Mark's Spock-like view of social interaction than Facebook's - and therefore Mark's - choice of the word "status" to qualify whether one is in a relationship or not?
p3172
aVRelationships are a trophy, an elusive uncodifiable mystery that this outsider tries so very hard to codify, literally as far as the millions of lines of code that go into creating his social networking site are concerned, but also in the more figurative sense.
p3173
aVAs more people selectively share more and more of themselves online, this is a subject aching for a clear-sighted, smartly-executed treatment, and David Fincher and Aaron Sorkin have provided exactly that treatment.
p3174
aVThat they've done so through a compelling human story, expertly acted, intensely re-watchable, and with plenty of LOLs along the way, is what makes The Social Network one of this year's few truly essential films.
p3175
aV\u000aWarner Bros. Pictures\u000aThere\u2019s no contest.
p3176
aVThe Dark Knight Rises, which opens next week, is the most hotly anticipated movie of the summer.
p3177
aVAnd yes, it lives up to the hype.
p3178
aVBut what\u2019s most astonishing is not Batman\u2019s new flying machine that zooms around skyscraper canyons, or a flirty Anne Hathaway poured into a skin-tight catsuit and stiletto boots, or a muzzled terrorist who looks like an S&M wrestler on steroids.
p3179
aVNo, the most breathtaking moment in the epic finale of the Batman trilogy is when Michael Caine weeps.
p3180
aVWhy?
p3181
aVThat would be a spoiler.
p3182
aVLet\u2019s just say the domestic bickering between Bruce Wayne (Christian Bale) and Alfred (Caine), his paternal butler, finally comes to an emotional head.
p3183
aV\u201cSir Michael Caine is always going to surprise you,\u201d says writer-director Christopher Nolan, on the phone from Los Angeles.
p3184
aV\u201cHaving worked with him on five movies, I knew he was going to bring something special to that scene.
p3185
aVBut when he performed it, it was absolutely gutting.
p3186
aVWe sat there in dailies and people were just sobbing.\u201d\u000aDon\u2019t be surprised to see Caine honoured at the Oscars, or to see The Dark Knight Rises vie for Best Picture.
p3187
aVSome franchises simply peter out.
p3188
aVNolan\u2019s trilogy, like the Lord of the Rings and Harry Potter sagas, has an engineered momentum that builds to a monumental climax.
p3189
aVAfter Batman Begins (2005) and The Dark Knight (2008), \u201cthis is not another episode in a series for us,\u201d says Nolan.
p3190
aV\u201cIt\u2019s the third act in one large story.\u201d\u000a\u000aIt also lands as the third act of a superhero summer, the last of three blockbusters after Marvel\u2019s The Avengers and The Amazing Spider-Man.
p3191
aVAs an action movie with physical and emotional heft, The Dark Knight Rises would appear to be the heavyweight contender.
p3192
aVBut The Avengers vaulted past the Potter, Pirates and Transformers franchises to become the third-highest-grossing movie in history after Avatar and Titanic, reaping a worldwide box office of $1.4 billion.
p3193
aVTough act to follow\u2014even though The Dark Knight earned over $1 billion.
p3194
aVTwenty years ago, who could have predicted that Hollywood would be a comic-book kingdom?
p3195
aVBlame it on Tim Burton\u2019s Batman (1989), which spawned a breed of dark, operatic spectacles for grown-up fanboys.
p3196
aVNow every self-respecting star needs a franchise and a mask, while comic-book culture ravages the ecology of the multiplex like an invasive species.
p3197
aVBut Nolan doesn\u2019t see his work as part of the trend.
p3198
aV\u201cWe never saw our films as comic-book movies,\u201d he says.
p3199
aV\u201cThe jumping-off point for Batman Begins was to make a movie, like any other adaptation.\u201d Yet he realizes that Rises\u2019 anchor spot in this superhero summer will affect its fate.
p3200
aV\u201cHow it\u2019s going to do, I have no idea,\u201d says the 41-year-old British director.
p3201
aV\u201cAll I can do is make the best film I can and hope people go along for the ride.\u201d\u000aThere is a lot riding on it.
p3202
aVEverything about The Dark Knight Rises seems to be an escalation of scale.
p3203
aVWith an estimated budget of $250 million, it clocks in at a mighty two hours, 44 minutes.
p3204
aVHalf the movie was filmed in the giant IMAX format, while the rest was shot on 70-mm and 35-mm film.
p3205
aVStubbornly old-school, Nolan refused to use digital video or 3D.
p3206
aVAnd he often chose bravura stunts over computer graphics\u2014from men dangling off a plane to 11,000 extras watching a football game as the field erupts with explosives.
p3207
aV\u201cAudiences are ruthless in their demand for freshness and novelty,\u201d says Nolan.
p3208
aV\u201cThey don\u2019t want to see the same thing again and again.
p3209
aVThey need to see it done in a different way and in a different place.
p3210
aVIt\u2019s a particular challenge with a sequel because you want familiar elements.\u201d\u000aAlong with Caine, they include Gary Oldman and Morgan Freeman who return as Wayne\u2019s two other father figures, Commissioner Gordon and his CEO Lucius Fox, respectively.
p3211
aV(\u201cHe\u2019s got a lot of fathers for an orphan,\u201d Nolan concedes.)
p3212
aVBut he has two new divas to play with: Hathaway\u2019s cat burglar Selina Kyle and philanthropist Miranda Tate (Marion Cotillard).
p3213
aVThe Dark Knight Rises picks up the story eight years after The Dark Knight.
p3214
aVHaving taken the fall for the death of district attorney Harvey Dent, Batman has vanished.
p3215
aVBruce Wayne, the tycoon behind the cowl, is now a bearded recluse who walks with a cane, holed up in Wayne Manor like a Gotham Howard Hughes.
p3216
aVWhen a ferocious new villain named Bane (Tom Hardy) lays siege to his financial empire, he hauls the batsuit out of storage.
p3217
aV(It\u2019s surprising how little screen time it gets\u2014first we wait for Batman\u2019s return, and later, while Wayne is imprisoned in a pit, we wait for him to rise again.)
p3218
aVScarred by a horrific injury (what comic-book villain isn\u2019t?
p3219
aV), Bane is masked by a contraption that pumps him with painkillers\u2014though its main effect is to turn his accented voice into an unearthly growl while channelling shades of Hannibal Lecter and Blue Velvet\u2019s Dennis Hopper.
p3220
aVBane\u2019s dialogue could benefit from subtitles, especially since he has to explain so much of the plot.
p3221
aVBatman\u2019s voice is distorted, too, so when they converse it\u2019s like listening to talking dogs.
p3222
aVNo matter: in the end, it all comes down to a fist fight.
p3223
aVThis time Batman is not just fighting crime, but saving his city from annihilation.
p3224
aVUnlike Heath Ledger\u2019s Joker, who picked off victims one by one for sheer sport, Bane is a terrorist on a doomsday mission, armed with a nuclear device stolen from Wayne Industries.
p3225
aV\u201cThat was an important part of giving this film the scale it needed,\u201d says Nolan.
p3226
aV\u201cWhen you\u2019re just stuck in Gotham, there\u2019s a danger things start to feel a bit village-y.\u201d\u000aBetween the spectre of epic terrorism and the allure of lethal women, there\u2019s more of a James Bond feel to this Batman opus than the others.
p3227
aV\u201cBut it\u2019s been there throughout,\u201d says Nolan.
p3228
aV\u201cWe\u2019ve been shamelessly plundering the Bond movies that I loved growing up.
p3229
aVIt would be more obvious if it had an English character at the head.
p3230
aVThis is a very American story.\u201d Even if this Brit director has stocked it with Brit actors\u2014Bale, Caine, Oldman and Hardy.
p3231
aV\u201cYou go for the right people for the job,\u201d he says, \u201cand they turn out to be English.\u201d\u000aThe pedigree of the cast imparts automatic gravitas.
p3232
aVAnd unlike so many comic-book movies, from Iron Man to The Avengers, Nolan\u2019s work is not a maze of jokey, postmodern asides.
p3233
aVThese are action movies freighted with dramatic and intellectual ambition.
p3234
aVHathaway\u2019s Catwoman may come on like a Bond girl, an agent of comic and erotic relief, but she has a subversive agenda.
p3235
aV\u201cThere\u2019s a storm coming,\u201d she tells Wayne.
p3236
aV\u201cYou and your friends better batten down the hatches, because when it hits, you\u2019re all gonna wonder how you ever thought you could live so large and leave so little to the rest of us.\u201d\u000aSound like Occupy Wall Street?
p3237
aVNolan did just that when he used 1,000 extras to film a pitched battle between cops and mercenaries in Manhattan.
p3238
aV\u201cWhen we went to Wall Street to film, the Occupy movement had grown up around it and there were ridiculous reports we had chosen it for that reason.
p3239
aVBut it took a year of planning, and the scene had been written two years before that.\u201d While 9/11 casts a long shadow over Gotham\u2019s scenes of terrorist destruction, the Occupy echoes are prescient.
p3240
aVNolan \u201chad no way of knowing,\u201d says Bale.
p3241
aVFilming just blocks from the protest, he recalls, \u201cI was looking at him\u2014how did you know?\u201d Gotham, explains Nolan, \u201cis a parallel world, and you wind up mirroring the concerns of the time.\u201d\u000aOne concern among those who care about cinema is that it\u2019s being overrun by comic-book franchises: the masked superhero has usurped the face of the movie star as Hollywood\u2019s most powerful icon.
p3242
aVWhich Nolan doesn\u2019t dispute.
p3243
aV\u201cWe\u2019re definitely well into a phase where our actors are not willing to brand themselves as movie stars the way actors of the past did,\u201d he says.
p3244
aV\u201cWhen you look at a guy like Christian, whether he\u2019s wearing a mask or not, this is one of our great actors.
p3245
aVBut he wants to be different in every film.
p3246
aVHe doesn\u2019t want the audience to go to a Christian Bale movie; he wants them to come see the character he\u2019s playing.
p3247
aVThat\u2019s true of most leading men working today.
p3248
aVThat wasn\u2019t true 20 years ago.\u201d\u000aNolan and Bale say they are both done with Batman\u2014although The Dark Knight Rises ends on a note that will allow another filmmaker to pick up the franchise where they left off.
p3249
aVBut Nolan, still a force behind Hollywood\u2019s superhero hegemony, is producing next year\u2019s Superman reboot, Man of Steel.
p3250
aVThe key to comic-book material, he insists, is to treat it as \u201ca source for movies of different types, not a genre\u2014if the comic-book movie is a genre, like the western, the audience will want something different.\u201d\u000aAs for his own directing future, \u201cI have no idea where I\u2019m going next,\u201d says Nolan.
p3251
aVDown the road, a Bond movie would not be out of the question.
p3252
aVAnd he doesn\u2019t even rule out 3D, if it\u2019s appropriate.
p3253
aV\u201cI\u2019m all about choice,\u201d he declares.
p3254
aV\u201cI don\u2019t like being told the way I should make a film.\u201d For one of the few filmmakers who can stand up to the studios, that may be the ultimate Hollywood superpower\u2014the ability to say no.
