aV\u000a\u000aTHE big-budget western of 2013 is here and it\u2019s less-than-overwhelming.
p3686
aV\u201cThe Lone Ranger\u201d stars Armie Hammer as the masked vigilante and Johnny Depp as his Indian sidekick, Tonto.
p3687
aVThe film opens in 1933 at a traveling sideshow where Tonto appears as part of the attraction.
p3688
aVHe\u2019s a bit older, of course.
p3689
aVAnd, this kid dressed up as Woody in \u201cToy Story\u201d asks Tonto if the legend of The Lone Ranger was true, or just a story.
p3690
aVTonto relates his adventures although his memory appears foggy at times.
p3691
aVHe\u2019s got to be over 90, maybe a hundred.
p3692
aVAnyway, John Reid (Hammer) is a prosecuting attorney determined to bring peace and justice to Texas as the transcontinental railroad is linked.
p3693
aVHe doesn\u2019t fare well after being deputized as a Texas Ranger by his brother so he can help bring an escaped killer to justice.
p3694
aVHis brother is killed, but Reid won\u2019t see red.
p3695
aVHe still believes that everyone is entitled to a fair trial.
p3696
aVHo hum!
p3697
aV\u201cThe Lone Ranger\u201d is the story of how Reid gets his mind changed on how to dispense the law.
p3698
aVTonto and Reid find a common interest, revenge.
p3699
aVBut, they initially don\u2019t get along.
p3700
aVDepp brings his usual quirkiness to the role of Tonto.
p3701
aVHe\u2019s often amusing.
p3702
aVBut, Hammer is plain vanilla as the masked lawman.
p3703
aVHe never quite makes the role truly his.
p3704
aVAnd, his transformation to vigilante trods along without much real emotion.
p3705
aVOn the down side, the film is way too long at two and a half hours.
p3706
aVWay too violent for Disney.
p3707
